    "body": "@romani \r\n> do we really need support of checkstyle_packages.xml - https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/master/src/xdocs/config.xml#L761 ?\r\n\r\nWe use this file to specify which packages to scan for 3rd party modules at https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/46fa8090954480eecdeb6e7367f0e30655853f42/src/main/java/com/puppycrawl/tools/checkstyle/PackageNamesLoader.java#L137-L147 .\r\n\r\nIf you are asking why don't we pull in all modules in the full classpath instead of restricting to a list of packages from users, than the only good reasons I have not to do it are:\r\n* Error message will be slightly more vague as it won't say what packages we were looking at. See: https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/pull/4886 which we just updated recently\r\n* Scanning the entire classpath could take longer as we will be looking at more classes and not restricting any by package.\r\n\r\nI will look into the second point.",

    "body": "@romani \r\n> do we really need support of checkstyle_packages.xml - https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/master/src/xdocs/config.xml#L761 ?\r\n\r\nWe use this file to specify which packages to scan for 3rd party modules at https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/46fa8090954480eecdeb6e7367f0e30655853f42/src/main/java/com/puppycrawl/tools/checkstyle/PackageNamesLoader.java#L137-L147 .\r\n\r\nIf you are asking why don't we pull in all modules in the full classpath instead of restricting to a list of packages from users, than the only good reasons I have not to do it are:\r\n* Error message will be slightly more vague as it won't say what packages we were looking at. See: https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/pull/4886 which we just updated recently\r\n* Scanning the entire classpath could take longer as we will be looking at more classes and not restricting any by package.\r\n\r\nI will look into the second point.",

    "updated_at": "2017-05-15T09:02:51Z",
    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "Clemens,\r\n\r\nThank for your review and comments.\r\nI apologize for the delay in replying.\r\n\r\nCan you clarify please - why condition  root.waitThis().size() > 0  (....not OR EQUAL)?\r\n\r\nLockGraphManager placed graph nodes on levels, calculate level \"width\" for visualisation and so on.\r\n\r\nThe source of nodes is the plugin of specific databases, at this moment - Postgres, Oracle and Exasol but this is not a final list (I hope) and in the future for other DBs there may be a situation of a \"degenerated\" graph that will consist of only one root node. In this case condition \"root.waitThis().size() >= 0\" cant be replaced with \"root.waitThis().size() > 0\". In other words I guess condition \"root.waitThis().size() >= 0\" now is not necessary at all - because its always true :) This is a legacy of LockGraphManager version of the manager that could not build degenerate graphs.\r\n\r\nCan you fix your PR or I can create patch too.\r\n\r\nThanks again for the review.\r\nAndrew.",

To provide client information it is better to use another approach. As I understood Exasol uses special connection properties (clientname & clientversion) to identify client. Oracle does the same. Check OracleDataSource.getInternalConnectionProperties method. This is a standard way to identify client while patching connection URL doesn't look very good.\r\nAdditionally DBUtils.getClientApplicationName allows to redefine client name in preferences (in some cases users want to mimic some other database client while working in DBeaver).\r\n",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "#1319 overrode the configuration (I merged it, funny enough).\n\nBut to add a (working) graphite reporter, one doesn't need to touch any java code:\n- Add dependency to pom\n\n``` xml\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>io.dropwizard</groupId>\n    <artifactId>dropwizard-metrics-graphite</artifactId>\n</dependency>\n```\n- and then add the reporter to the yaml\n\n``` yaml\nmetrics:\n  reporters:\n    - type: graphite\n      host: localhost\n      port: 2003\n      prefix: my-awesome-service\n```\n\nSo at this point, I think the example application is _wrong_, unless @joschi remembers why it was done 8 months ago.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "body": "#1319 overrode the configuration (I merged it, funny enough).\n\nBut to add a (working) graphite reporter, one doesn't need to touch any java code:\n- Add dependency to pom\n\n``` xml\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>io.dropwizard</groupId>\n    <artifactId>dropwizard-metrics-graphite</artifactId>\n</dependency>\n```\n- and then add the reporter to the yaml\n\n``` yaml\nmetrics:\n  reporters:\n    - type: graphite\n      host: localhost\n      port: 2003\n      prefix: my-awesome-service\n```\n\nSo at this point, I think the example application is _wrong_, unless @joschi remembers why it was done 8 months ago.\n",

    "body": "@gregw, In General, it looks good for me and it works. I have configured the client with the following code:\r\n```\r\nHttpCompliance compliance = HttpCompliance.CUSTOM0;\r\ncompliance.sections().clear();\r\ncompliance.sections().add(HttpComplianceSection.RFC7230_3_2_CASE_INSENSITIVE_FIELD_NAME);\r\ncompliance.sections().add(HttpComplianceSection.USE_CASE_INSENSITIVE_FIELD_VALUE_CACHE);\r\n\r\nthis.httpClient = createClient(pool);\r\nthis.httpClient.setHttpCompliance(compliance);\r\n```\r\n\r\nIt seems to be a little bit ugly that I have to clear the `HttpCompliance.CUSTOM0` list beforehand. In general, I think it would be useful to have a compliance mode that is as weak as possible. This will ensure that the jetty client behaves similarly to real browsers. They are also loading and displaying web pages which has many HTTP compliance issues by just ignoring those errors.\r\n",

    "body": "@btd I think the test should produce an http request with a valid etag.\n\nProbably start by requesting the resource once normally, get the ETag produced.\nThen request a second time, but with the ETag from the first in the request's `If-None-Match` header.\n\nThat header value should also include the extra `--gzip` suffix that your patch fixes.\n\nThen assert that the response status code (and headers?) on this second request indicate that the resource is unchanged (status code `304 Not Modified`) with no body content.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Why aren't we using https://connect2id.com/products/nimbus-jose-jwt \r\n\r\nTo be honest, I don't have a perfectly valid excuse. I didn't come across it in the beginning when looking through candidate libraries and as such evaluated only jjwt which lacks support for JDK9+ and java-jwt whis is only tested with java 8. Also, we have been traditionally reluctant to bringing in dependencies and the scope of this work seemed to be just not large enough to justify the effort. Finally, there will not be any need to implement cryptographic primitives here, so I evaluated the risk of a significant implementation error to be low enough. \r\n\r\nStill, I will not object too much if we feel like `nimbus-jose-jwt` is a better option. I've come across the implementation lately, when looking into JWE implementations and I think it's a solid one. The only \"issue\" I see is that it depends on [`json-smart`](https://netplex.github.io/json-smart) which we would need to bring in also. Can I elicit additional opinions here: @jaymode , @tvernum  ?\r\n\r\n> I noticed it is already pulled in as a transitive dependency prob for kerberos ./gradlew :x-pack:plugin:security:dependencies\r\n\r\nWe use it as a test dependency only, for Kerberos tests, we don't ship it with Elasticsearch. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",

Rather than mix/match storage classes between different snapshots in the same repository as there's not much value in this mixed approach for perceived lifecycling patterns (keep all monthlies as standard class, subsequent inter-month snaps as reduced redundancy/IA,etc) due to the incremental nature of snapshot files relying on other files in the repository without much external visibility. I'm not sure if we want to describe the repository layout in enough detail to address this.\r\n\r\nI don't think that we should describe how we write objects to the repository and I don't think it would help anyway.     "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> we do not describe how we write objects to the repository, so after adding this I think users will still struggle to understand the implications of the various options for storage_class. I'm not sure if we want to describe the repository layout in enough detail to address this.\r\n\r\nI don't think that we should describe how we write objects to the repository and I don't think it would help anyway. But I think it is valuable for users to understand the implication of changing the storage class on an existing repository, ie that the storage class is applied to new snapshotted files only. The explanation of incremental snapshots looks sufficient to me.\r\n\r\n> I do not think we should explicitly recommend setting all objects to the same storage class. It makes the most sense to me, but the choice of storage class is irrelevant to Elasticsearch, and I think users should feel free to set it to whatever they want according to their usage.\r\n\r\nI agree that the choice of storage class is out of scope and I don't think this change recommend to use a specific storage class? I still think that we must indicate a) what is the default storage class, b) changing the setting on an existing repository only change the storage class for newly created objects resulting in a mixed usage of storage classes in the repo and c) users may prefer use Lifecycle Policies to manage storage classes.",

I'm not sure if we want to describe the repository layout in enough detail to address this.\r\n\r\nI don't think that we should describe how we write objects to the repository and I don't think it would help anyway. But I think it is valuable for users to understand the implication of changing the storage class on an existing repository, ie that the storage class is applied to new snapshotted files only. The explanation of incremental snapshots looks sufficient to me.\r\n\r\n> I do not think we should explicitly recommend setting all objects to the same storage class. It makes the most sense to me, but the choice of storage class is irrelevant to Elasticsearch, and I think users should feel free to set it to whatever they want according to their usage.\r\n\r\nI agree that the choice of storage class is out of scope and I don't think this change recommend to use a specific storage class?     "body": "I only wonder if it's also good to provide a recommendation to set all files in a repository to one storage class, via the storage class setting initially and with AWS API and storage class setting if changing storage class at a later point. Rather than mix/match storage classes between different snapshots in the same repository as there's not much value in this mixed approach for perceived lifecycling patterns (keep all monthlies as standard class, subsequent inter-month snaps as reduced redundancy/IA,etc) due to the incremental nature of snapshot files relying on other files in the repository without much external visibility.     "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> I wonder if this should be a module or just pushed inside core es. As a module it would not be possible to define new metrics in a plugin so I'd vote for moving it to core. If you disagree then there are some work to do to make sure that the transport and rest client can use the query/response defined in the module.\r\n\r\n@jimczi thanks, I went ahead and did the SPI work needed to make the rest client aware of the namedXContent objects introduced in this feature in case we want to keept is as a module for now in the last commit. Let me know if you think there is anything else to add to this. \r\n\r\nI'm still undecided on the module vs. core question, my gut feeling is that this is something similar to percolate that is good to keep in a separate module. We could either \r\n* move just the EvaluationMetric interface to core (feels a bit weird to me)\r\n* decide to publish the module so people can use those interfaces in their plugins if needed (from reading #27527 I get the impression that we seem to do this for some modules) \r\n* or we simply decide that at this point we don't want to support defining custom metrics and maybe add that capabilities later\r\n\r\nI'm also fine with moving all code to its own package in core\r\nI'd like to get some feedback from @colings86 and/or @clintongormley what they think about this too.",
